<subSubSection id="56B7651E0E39FF9BFF06AA1AFC59FD2E" pageId="2" pageNumber="143" type="description">
<paragraph id="1E1236950E39FF9BFF06AA1AFD0BFE77" blockId="2.[143,760,266,1300]" pageId="2" pageNumber="143">
The first described species is not documented by a deposited 
<typeStatus id="C11688370E39FF9BFE80AA39FEC7FED3" box="[265,314,297,318]" pageId="2" pageNumber="143">type</typeStatus>
specimen, and the only information that can be gleaned from Koch’s drawing published in 1842 is the character of the first leg with two long distoventral sword setae and a curved terminal segment.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1E1236950E39FF9BFF21AAB4FE1FFC68" blockId="2.[143,760,266,1300]" pageId="2" pageNumber="143">
As mentioned above, the second species of the genus, 
<taxonomicName id="D9AD4D160E39FF9BFF68AAD2FED9FE3A" authorityName="Koenike" authorityYear="1883" box="[225,292,450,471]" class="Arachnida" family="Hygrobatidae" genus="Atractides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="143" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ovalis">
<emphasis id="2CD9EA870E39FF9BFF68AAD2FED9FE3A" box="[225,292,450,471]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="143">ovalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, owes its origin to Neuman’s error, who regarded the ventral morphology of a deutonymph depicted by 
<bibRefCitation id="7A3C4B640E39FF9BFE95A910FE3AFDF8" author="Kramer PM" box="[284,455,511,533]" pageId="2" pageNumber="143" pagination="263 - 332" refId="ref177799" refString="Kramer PM. 1875. Beitrage zur Naturgeschichte der Hydrachniden. Archiv fur Naturgeschichte 41 (1): 263 - 332." type="journal article" year="1875">Kramer (1875)</bibRefCitation>
as a diagnostic adult feature. The specimen depicted by Neuman as 
<taxonomicName id="D9AD4D160E39FF9BFD18A90FFF11FDBF" authorityName="Koch" authorityYear="1837" class="Arachnida" family="Hygrobatidae" genus="Megapus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Acari" pageId="2" pageNumber="143" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinipes">
<emphasis id="2CD9EA870E39FF9BFD18A90FFF11FDBF" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="143">Megapus spinipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and baptized by Koenike in 1883 as 
<taxonomicName id="D9AD4D160E39FF9BFD19A92DFD0DFDBF" authorityName="Koenike" authorityYear="1883" box="[656,752,573,594]" class="Arachnida" family="Hygrobatidae" genus="Atractides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="143" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ovalis">
<emphasis id="2CD9EA870E39FF9BFD19A92DFD0DFDBF" box="[656,752,573,594]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="143">A. ovalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, is lost. Further complicating the situation, Koenike based his first description on specimens from 
<collectingCountry id="66BA76050E39FF9BFD1EA96AFD0FFD7D" box="[663,754,634,656]" name="Canada" pageId="2" pageNumber="143">Canada</collectingCountry>
, which he recognized in 1908 as representing ‘ 
<taxonomicName id="D9AD4D160E39FF9BFD25A989FF28FD21" authorityName="Koenike" authorityYear="1908" class="Arachnida" family="Hygrobatidae" genus="Atractides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="143" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crassipalpis">
<emphasis id="2CD9EA870E39FF9BFD25A989FF28FD21" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="143">crassipalpis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’, a different species. The same year he published figures of a well-defined, clearly recognizable 
<taxonomicName id="D9AD4D160E39FF9BFF06A9E5FF0FFCE7" authorityName="Koenike" authorityYear="1883" box="[143,242,757,778]" class="Arachnida" family="Hygrobatidae" genus="Atractides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="143" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ovalis">
<emphasis id="2CD9EA870E39FF9BFF06A9E5FF0FFCE7" box="[143,242,757,778]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="143">A. ovalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. All authors who had used this name in the previous 25 years could therefore not have known its morphological details, and in many cases probably based their identifications on the misunderstood character of number of acetabula.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1E1236950E39FF9BFF21A89EFDD1FB97" blockId="2.[143,760,266,1300]" pageId="2" pageNumber="143">
During this period, researchers discovered the main lines of morphological diversification in the genus and described ten additional species (nine from Europe and one from 
<collectingCountry id="66BA76050E39FF9BFEA4A8FAFE41FBED" box="[301,444,1002,1024]" name="Madagascar" pageId="2" pageNumber="143">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
). Apart from 
<taxonomicName id="D9AD4D160E39FF9BFDDDA8FAFF2AFBF2" authority="Thon (1901)" authorityName="Thon" authorityYear="1901" class="Arachnida" family="Hygrobatidae" genus="Atractides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="143" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gabretae">
<emphasis id="2CD9EA870E39FF9BFDDDA8FAFD48FC12" box="[596,693,1002,1023]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="143">gabretae</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="7A3C4B640E39FF9BFD35A8FAFF2AFBF2" author="Thon K" pageId="2" pageNumber="143" pagination="279 - 285" refId="ref181972" refString="Thon K. 1901. Neue Hydrachniden aus dem Bohmer Wald. Zoologischer Anzeiger 24 (643): 279 - 285." type="journal article" year="1901">Thon (1901)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(probably a malformation) they are all clearly defined by important peculiarities, such as presence of dorsal idiosomal sclerites, shape of palps and first legs, and morphology of the genital area.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1E1236950E39FF9BFF21AF94FB92FE01" blockId="2.[143,760,266,1300]" lastBlockId="2.[807,1423,195,707]" pageId="2" pageNumber="143">
It seems likely that for many years the name of the type species 
<taxonomicName id="D9AD4D160E39FF9BFEA2AFB3FE75FB55" authorityName="Koch" authorityYear="1837" box="[299,392,1187,1208]" class="Arachnida" family="Hygrobatidae" genus="Megapus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Acari" pageId="2" pageNumber="143" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinipes">
<emphasis id="2CD9EA870E39FF9BFEA2AFB3FE75FB55" box="[299,392,1187,1208]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="143">spinipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been used as a dumping ground for a variety of not easily determinable specimens often listed in faunistic surveys as single finds. Evidence for this is provided by the numerous specimens given this name in the main European collections, which represent either unidentifiable juveniles and females, or aberrant, homoiomorphic males of different species. Koch’s description probably referred to one of the more widely distributed species. A dubious benefit of the unavailability of his type specimen is that it helps avoid further taxonomic changes and confusion. In this paper, 
<taxonomicName id="D9AD4D160E39FF9BFB9CAA89FB11FE42" baseAuthorityName="Piersig" baseAuthorityYear="1894" box="[1045,1260,409,431]" class="Arachnida" family="Hygrobatidae" genus="Atractides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="143" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinipes">
<emphasis id="2CD9EA870E39FF9BFB9CAA89FB11FE42" box="[1045,1260,409,431]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="143">Atractides spinipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is redescribed on the basis of a 
<typeStatus id="C11688370E39FF9BFC64AAA9FBBBFE23" box="[1005,1094,441,462]" pageId="2" pageNumber="143">neotype</typeStatus>
from a large population collected in southern 
<collectingCountry id="66BA76050E39FF9BFB89AAC7FB91FE01" box="[1024,1132,471,492]" name="Germany" pageId="2" pageNumber="143">Germany</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1E1236950E39FF9BFCC9AAE5FC59FD2E" blockId="2.[807,1423,195,707]" pageId="2" pageNumber="143">
The taxonomic history of this species is unfortunately not atypical, with an initial published name used as a wastepaper bin for all poorly identified specimens. Consequently, early descriptions of the larval stages of 
<taxonomicName id="D9AD4D160E39FF9BFC4BA960FB12FD6B" authority="(Piersig, 1894)" baseAuthorityName="Piersig" baseAuthorityYear="1894" box="[962,1263,624,646]" class="Arachnida" family="Hygrobatidae" genus="Atractides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="143" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinipes">
<emphasis id="2CD9EA870E39FF9BFC4BA960FBC2FD6B" box="[962,1087,624,646]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="143">A. spinipes</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="7A3C4B640E39FF9BFBD9A960FB1AFD6B" author="Piersig GR" box="[1104,1255,624,646]" pageId="2" pageNumber="143" pagination="370 - 378" refId="ref180364" refString="Piersig GR. 1894. Hydrachnologische Berichtigungen. Zoologischer Anzeiger 17 (459): 370 - 378." type="journal article" year="1894">Piersig, 1894</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="D9AD4D160E39FF9BFAA5A960FC2DFD48" authority="(Piersig, 1896)" baseAuthorityName="Piersig" baseAuthorityYear="1896" class="Arachnida" family="Hygrobatidae" genus="Atractides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="143" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ovalis">
<emphasis id="2CD9EA870E39FF9BFAA5A960FA72FD68" box="[1324,1423,624,645]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="143">A. ovalis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="7A3C4B640E39FF9BFCA6A99FFC35FD48" author="Piersig GR" box="[815,968,655,677]" pageId="2" pageNumber="143" pagination="7" refId="ref180383" refString="Piersig GR. 1896. Deutschlands Hydrachniden. Zoologica, Stuttgart (1896 - 1899) 19 (22): 7 + 1 - 601." type="journal article" year="1896">Piersig, 1896</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
cannot be included in the taxonomic discussion.
</paragraph>
